            "title": "Reconstruction-free compressive vision for surveillance applications",
            "abstract": [
                "Introduction.Targeted Applications ; Problem Motivation ; Organization -- Compressed Sensing Fundamentals. Foundations of Compressed Sensing ; Related Convex Problems ; CS Reconstruction as Bayesian Inference ; Model-Based Compressed Sensing ; Blind Compressed Sensing ; Sensors for Compressive Image and Video Capture ; Single-Pixel Camera ; Infrared and Hyperspectral Compressive Sensing Cameras ; Medical Imaging and MRI ; 4D Light Fields, Digital Holography, and Microscopy ; Non-Convex Reconstruction Algorithms ; Greedy Solvers ; Graphical Methods ;",
                "Video Reconstruction Algorithms ; SPArse and Low Rank Decomposition Via Compressive Sensing (SPArCS) ; CS MUltiscale VIdeo recovery (CS-MUVI) ; Background Subtraction ; Other Methods ; Performance of CS Reconstruction ; Computation Speed ; Cramer-Rao Lower Bound ; Phase Transition ; Sparse Recovery in Noise ; Recovery of Compressible Signals ; Deep Learning for Compressed Sensing Reconstruction ; Convolutional Neural Networks ; RBM for Compressed Sensing Reconstruction ; Stacked Denoising Autoencoder for CS Reconstruction ; DeepInverse and DeepCodec ; Image Recovery Using RIDE ;",
                "Direct Inference on Compressive Measurements Using CNNs ; Classification on Compressive Measurements via Deep Boltzmann Machines ; Compressive Sensing for Visual Question Answering -- Conclusion. Final Remarks and Further Reading.",
                "CS Recovery using PixelCNN++ and MAP Inference ; The ReconNet Architecture ; Summary -- Computer Vision and Image Processing for Surveillance Applications. Surveillance Overview ; Classification and Detection Algorithms ; MACH Filter ; Deep Boltzmann Machines ; Tracking Algorithms ; State-Space Model of the Tracking Problem ; Kalman Filter ; Particle Filter ; Summary --  Toward Compressive Vision. Smashed Filter ; Performance of the Smashed Filter ; Spatio-Temporal Smashed Filters ; Reconstruction-Free Compressive Tracking Algorithm ; Track-Before-Detect Particle Filter ; Experimental Results ; Classification ;",
                "Compressed sensing (CS) allows signals and images to be reliably inferred from undersampled measurements. Exploiting CS allows the creation of new types of high-performance sensors including infrared cameras and magnetic resonance imaging systems. Advances in computer vision and deep learning have enabled new applications of automated systems. In this book, we introduce reconstruction-free compressive vision, where image processing and computer vision algorithms are embedded directly in the compressive domain, without the need for first reconstructing the measurements into images or video. Reconstruction of CS images is computationally expensive and adds to system complexity. Therefore, reconstruction-free compressive vision is an appealing alternative particularly for power-aware systems and bandwidth-limited applications that do not have on-board post-processing computational capabilities. Engineers must balance maintaining algorithm performance while minimizing both the number of measurements needed and the computational requirements of the algorithms. Our study explores the intersection of compressed sensing and computer vision, with the focus on applications in surveillance and autonomous navigation. Other applications are also discussed at the end and a comprehensive list of references including survey papers are given for further reading"
            ],
